Step 1b¶
Now we create the target column Returns and the respective lagged values from 1 to 6 days. We apply the same reasoning as in the previous projects, where we used 6 lags to capture the returns' behavior from the past business week. We deem including higher-order lags redudant and potentially even introducing noise to the model instead of adding information.


Additionally, as in the previous projects, we consider the task to be an autoregression problem.



















In [855]:



     


# Calculate the returns

for i in range(6):
  data[f'Returns_Lag_{i+1}'] = data.loc[:, 'Returns'].shift(i+1)

# Remove missing values
data = data.dropna()

Naturally, including the 6 lagged values of returns resulted in shortening the initial dataset by 7 observations (1 for creating the column Returns and 6 for the respective lags).


We split the data in the proportion of 80% for training set and 20% for test set. Hence, our test sample starts in May 2022. The advantage of such a split is that the period of highest (clustered) volatility of March 2020 is captured in the training set. Therefore we expect our models to learn both prosperity and crisis periods.


To get an idea of the potential modeling issues that may occur due to the data characteristics, we visualize the data.

As per the assigned task, our data in the first two steps is supposed to have an issue of data leakage. The issue is that during training we (deliberately, in this case) include the data that should not have been "seen" by the model and used to learn data patterns, e.g., by incorporating future data or including the target variable in features, directly or indirectly (via feature engineering). This, in turn, may lead to overly optimistic model performance on the training set and consequently a significant performance drop on the test set.


We decided to create data leakage by shifting the first lagged return by 1 observation so that we actually train the model to predict today's return using today's return and its lagged values from 2 to 6 days.

Step 1c¶
In this subtask we create the Deep Learning models:


    

  • MLP
    • 

  • LSTM
    • 

  • CNN with GAF representation.
    • 



It is beneficial for all models to be trained on scaled data, therefore we apply min-max scaling.


We use the following model specifications:


    

  • MLP:
      

    • 1 hidden dense layer with 64 neurons and rectified linear unit activation function
      • 

    • 1 output dense layer with 1 neuron
      • 

    • Adam optimizer
      • 

    • MSE loss function (which also ensures comparability with the baseline linear regression model)
      • 

    • The model is trained in 20 epochs and in minibatches of 32 observations;
      • 

    

    • 

  • LSTM:
      

    • 1 LSTM layer with 64 neurons and rectified linear unit activation function
      • 

    • 1 output dense layer with 1 neuron
      • 

    • Adam optimizer
      • 

    • MSE loss function
      • 

    • The model is trained in 20 epochs and in minibatches of 32 observations;
      • 

    

    • 

  • CNN with GAF representation:
      

    • 1 Convolutional 2D layer with 32 neurons, kernel size 3$\times$3 and rectified linear unit activation function
      • 

    • 1 max-pooling 2D layer with kernel size 2$\times$2
      • 

    • 1 hidden dense layer with 64 neurons and rectified linear unit activation function
      • 

    • 1 output dense layer with 1 neuron and linear activation function
      • 

    • Adam optimizer
      • 

    • MSE loss function
      • 

    • We apply a computational tweak so that the training set size is divisible by the batch size.
      • 

    

    • 




















In [859]:



     


# Normalize the data separately for each model
scaler_mlp = MinMaxScaler()

# MLP Model
X_train_mlp = scaler_mlp.fit_transform(np.array(X_train))
y_train_mlp = scaler_mlp.fit_transform(np.array(y_train).reshape(-1, 1))
X_test_mlp = scaler_mlp.transform(np.array(X_test).reshape(-1, 1))
y_test_mlp = scaler_mlp.transform(np.array(y_test).reshape(-1, 1))

scaler_lstm = MinMaxScaler()

# LSTM Model
X_train_lstm = scaler_lstm.fit_transform(np.array(X_train))
y_train_lstm = scaler_lstm.fit_transform(np.array(y_train).reshape(-1, 1))
X_test_lstm = scaler_lstm.transform(np.array(X_test).reshape(-1, 1))
y_test_lstm = scaler_lstm.transform(np.array(y_test).reshape(-1, 1))

# CNN based on GAF Model
window_size = 6  # Length of the sliding window

# Normalize the data
scaler_cnn = MinMaxScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler_cnn.fit_transform(np.array(X_train))
X_test_scaled = scaler_cnn.transform(np.array(X_test))
y_train_cnn = scaler_cnn.fit_transform(np.array(y_train).reshape(-1, 1))
y_test_cnn = scaler_cnn.transform(np.array(y_test).reshape(-1, 1))

# Generate GAF images
gaf = GramianAngularField(image_size=window_size, method='difference')
X_train_gaf = gaf.fit_transform(X_train_scaled)
X_test_gaf = gaf.transform(X_test_scaled)

# Reshape the data for CNN input [samples, width, height, channels]
X_train_cnn = X_train_gaf.reshape(-1, window_size, window_size, 1)
X_test_cnn = X_test_gaf.reshape(-1, window_size, window_size, 1)

# Split the data into training and testing sets for CNN

# Train and evaluate the models
# MLP Model
mlp_model = Sequential()
mlp_model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu', input_dim=6))
mlp_model.add(Dense(1))
mlp_model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse')
mlp_model.fit(X_train_mlp, y_train_mlp, epochs=20, batch_size=32, verbose=False)

# LSTM Model
lstm_model = Sequential()
lstm_model.add(LSTM(64, activation='relu', input_shape=(1, 6)))
lstm_model.add(Dense(1))
lstm_model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse')
lstm_model.fit(X_train_lstm.reshape(-1, 1, 6), y_train_lstm, epochs=20, batch_size=32, verbose=False)

# CNN Model
cnn_model = Sequential()
cnn_model.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(window_size, window_size, 1)))
cnn_model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
cnn_model.add(Flatten())
cnn_model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))
cnn_model.add(Dense(1, activation='linear'))
cnn_model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mean_squared_error')
cnn_model.fit(X_train_cnn, y_train_cnn, epochs=20, batch_size=32, verbose=False)

# Evaluation
mlp_train_loss = mlp_model.evaluate(X_train_mlp.reshape(len(y_train), 6), y_train_mlp)
lstm_train_loss = lstm_model.evaluate(X_train_lstm.reshape(-1, 1, 6), y_train_lstm)
cnn_train_loss = cnn_model.evaluate(X_train_cnn, y_train_cnn)

print('MLP Train Loss:', mlp_train_loss)
print('LSTM Train Loss:', lstm_train_loss)
print('CNN Train Loss:', cnn_train_loss)

# Evaluation
mlp_test_loss = mlp_model.evaluate(X_test_mlp.reshape(len(y_test), 6), y_test)
lstm_test_loss = lstm_model.evaluate(X_test_lstm.reshape(-1, 1, 6), y_test)
cnn_test_loss = cnn_model.evaluate(X_test_cnn, y_test_cnn)

print('MLP Test Loss:', mlp_test_loss)
print('LSTM Test Loss:', lstm_test_loss)
print('CNN Test Loss:', cnn_test_loss)

We can clearly see the effect of data leakage: train losses of all models are nearly 0, whereas test losses are much higher:


    

  • Linear Regression's test loss is 2.3*10^30 times greater than train loss (0.0 because of the artificially introduced perfect multicollinearity between one feature of X_train and y_train)
    • 

  • MLP's test loss is over 16 thousand times greater than train loss
    • 

  • LSTM's test loss is almost 30 thousand times greater than train loss
    • 

  • CNN's test loss is nearly 4 times greater than train loss.
    • 



Without any hyperparameter tuning, the baseline linear regression model is overall the best-performer, followed by CNN with GAF representation. Conversely, MLP and LSTM models have much greater test loss. In the wake of the findings from the previous project it is quite a surprising result since CNN was not expected to work well for financial data.


It is possible that MLP and LSTM would perform better after hyperparameter tuning, however to maintain computational feasibility we skip this step.























Step 1d¶
Finally we test trading strategies. We assume trading without leverage, i.e., buying


The strategy is as follows: if the predicted next-day return is above the current-day return, buy; sell short if the predicted next-day return is below the current-day return.


We set a benchmark buy-and-hold strategy, whose return is 22.79% over the test period.























MLP¶
First, we test the strategy on the MLP model.



















In [862]:



     


# Perform backtest
initial_capital = 10000  # Initial capital in USD
current_capital = initial_capital
shares = 0
total_trades = 0
winning_trades = 0
# Retrieve the prices in the testing period
train_size = int(len(X_train_mlp))
test_prices = data['Close'][-len(y_test):]
X_test_mlp_reshaped = X_test_mlp.reshape(len(y_test), 6)

# Predict the next day's return using the MLP model
predicted_price = mlp_model.predict(X_test_mlp_reshaped, verbose=False)
predicted_price = scaler_mlp.inverse_transform(predicted_price)

for i in range(len(y_test)):
    # Buy signal: If the predicted return increase is above a threshold, buy shares
    if predicted_price[i] > y_test[i]:
        shares_to_buy = int(current_capital / test_prices[i])
        shares += shares_to_buy
        current_capital -= shares_to_buy * test_prices[i]
        total_trades += 1
        winning_trades += 1

    # Sell signal: If the predicted return decrease is below a threshold, sell shares
    elif predicted_price[i] < y_test[i]:
        current_capital += shares * test_prices[i]
        shares = 0
        total_trades += 1

# Calculate the final portfolio value
final_portfolio_value = current_capital + shares * test_prices[-1]
percent_gain = ((final_portfolio_value - initial_capital) / initial_capital) * 100

# Print the results
results_mlp_df = pd.DataFrame([initial_capital, final_portfolio_value, percent_gain, total_trades, winning_trades],
                              index=['Initial Capital', 'Final Portfolio Value', 'Percentage Gain', 'Total Trades', 'Winning Trades'],
                              columns=['Value'])
results_mlp_df.round(2)

def create_lstm_model(n_input):
  """
  Creates a LSTM model for prediction.

  :param n_input: specifies number of features
  :return: model
  """
  # Train the LSTM model
  lstm_model = Sequential()
  lstm_model.add(LSTM(64, activation='relu', input_shape=(1, n_input)))
  lstm_model.add(Dense(1))
  lstm_model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse')
  return lstm_model

def create_mlp_model(n_input):
  """
  Creates a MLP model for prediction.

  :param n_input: specifies number of features
  :return: model
  """
  model = Sequential()
  model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu', input_dim=n_input))
  model.add(Dense(1))
  model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse')
  return model

def create_cnn_model(n_input=6):
  """
  Creates a CNN model for prediction.

  :param n_input: specifies number of features
  :return: model
  """
  cnn_model = Sequential([
      Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(n_input, n_input, 1)),
      MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)),
      Flatten(),
      Dense(100, activation='relu'),
      Dense(1)
  ])
  cnn_model.compile(loss='mean_squared_error', optimizer='adam')

  return cnn_model



     























The code to perform a non anchored walk forward has been written in a generic way.

# Helper functions to get data with the correct shapes
def get_lstm_data(X, y, train=True):
  X_train = scaler_lstm.fit_transform(np.array(X))
  y_train = scaler_lstm.fit_transform(np.array(y).reshape(-1, 1))
  X_test = scaler_lstm.transform(np.array(X).reshape(-1, 1))
  y_test = scaler_lstm.transform(np.array(y).reshape(-1, 1))

  if train:
    return X_train, y_train
  else:
    return X_test, y_test

def get_gaf_data(X, y, train=True):
  # CNN based on GAF Model
  window_size = 6  # Length of the sliding window

  # Normalize the data
  X_train_scaled = scaler_cnn.fit_transform(np.array(X_train))
  X_test_scaled = scaler_cnn.transform(np.array(X_test))
  y_train_cnn = scaler_cnn.fit_transform(np.array(y_train).reshape(-1, 1))
  y_test_cnn = scaler_cnn.transform(np.array(y_test).reshape(-1, 1))

  # Generate GAF images
  gaf = GramianAngularField(image_size=window_size, method='difference')
  X_train_gaf = gaf.fit_transform(X_train_scaled)
  X_test_gaf = gaf.transform(X_test_scaled)

  # Reshape the data for CNN input [samples, width, height, channels]
  X_train_cnn = X_train_gaf.reshape(-1, window_size, window_size, 1)
  X_test_cnn = X_test_gaf.reshape(-1, window_size, window_size, 1)
  if train:
    return X_train_cnn, y_train_cnn
  else:
    return X_test_cnn, y_test_cnn

def walk_forward(df, model, ModelType, n_train, n_test):
    """
    Peform Non-anchored Walk Forward on observation data using parameters

    :param df: dataframe of securities data
    :param model: model used for prediction using walk forward
    :param ModelType: type of the model passed for walk forward
    :param n_train: number of observations for train
    :param n_test: number of parameters for test
    :return: dataframe
    """

    time_backtest = np.array([]).astype("datetime64[ns]", copy=False)
    pred_backtest = []
    ret_backtest = []

    #print("Len Y", len(y))

    for i in range(0, len(y)-n_train, n_test):
        X_train, X_test = X[i:(i + n_train)], X[(i + n_train):(i + n_train + n_test)]
        y_train, y_test = y[i:(i + n_train)], y[(i + n_train):(i + n_train + n_test)]

        # Read the index values
        #print("Len:", len(X_train))
        test_time = df.iloc[(i + n_train):(i + n_train + n_test), 0:1].index.values
        Ret_vector = df.iloc[(i + n_train):(i + n_train + n_test), 6:7].values

        print(i,
              #i + (n_train), i + n_train + n_test,
              "ite ",
              i / n_test,
              " --start test:",
              test_time[0].astype('datetime64[D]'),
              " --end test",
              test_time[-1].astype('datetime64[D]'),
              " ----- ",
              X_train.shape,
              y_train.shape,
              X_test.shape,
              y_test.shape,
              test_time.shape,
              Ret_vector.shape,
              )

        # Fit the model
        if ModelType == 'MLP':
            try:
                model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=20, batch_size=32, verbose=False)
                y_pred = model.predict(X_test, verbose=False)
                time_backtest = np.append(time_backtest, test_time.flatten())
                pred_backtest = np.append(pred_backtest, y_pred.flatten())
                ret_backtest = np.append(ret_backtest, Ret_vector.flatten())
            except Exception as e:
                print("Error occurred during MLP model training:", e)
                # Reshape the data to have smaller dimensions
                X_train, X_test = X_train.reshape(-1, 1), X_test.reshape(-1, 1)
                print("Reshape sucessful")

        elif ModelType == 'LSTM':
            try:
                test_time = df.iloc[(i + len(X_train)):(i + n_train + n_test), 0:1].index.values
                Ret_vector = df.iloc[(i + n_train):(i + n_train + n_test), 6:7].values
                X_train_lstm, y_train_lstm = get_lstm_data(X_train, y_train)
                X_train_lstm = X_train_lstm.reshape(n_train, 1, n_input)
                model.fit(X_train_lstm, y_train_lstm, epochs=20, batch_size=32, verbose=False)
                # Predictions on the test data
                X_test_lstm, y_test_lstm = get_lstm_data(X_test, y_test, False)
                y_pred = model.predict(X_test_lstm.reshape(n_test, 1, n_input), verbose=False)

                time_backtest = np.append(time_backtest, test_time.flatten())
                pred_backtest = np.append(pred_backtest, y_pred.flatten())
                ret_backtest = np.append(ret_backtest, Ret_vector.flatten())

                print(time_backtest.shape, pred_backtest.shape, ret_backtest.shape)
            except Exception as e:
                print("Error occurred during LSTM model training:", e)
                # Reshape the data to have smaller dimensions
                X_train_lstm, X_test_lstm = X_train_lstm.reshape(-1, 1, n_input), X_test_lstm.reshape(-1, 1, n_input)
                print("Reshape sucessful")

        elif ModelType == 'CNN':
            try:
                # Normalize the target variable
                test_time = df.iloc[(i+n_train):(i+n_train+n_test), 0:1].index.values
                Ret_vector = df.iloc[(i+n_train):(i+n_train+n_test), 6:7].values

                scaler = MinMaxScaler()
                target = scaler.fit_transform(y.values.reshape(-1, 1)).flatten()
                X_train_GAF, y_train_GAF = get_gaf_data(X, y)
                # CNN model
                model.fit(X_train_GAF, y_train_GAF, epochs=20, batch_size=32, verbose=False)

                # Predict the target variable using the CNN model
                X_test_GAF, y_test_GAF = get_gaf_data(X, y, False)
                y_test_pred = model.predict(X_test_GAF)

                pred_backtest = np.append(pred_backtest, y_test_pred.flatten())
                time_backtest = np.append(time_backtest, test_time.flatten())
                ret_backtest = np.append(ret_backtest, Ret_vector.flatten())
                print(len(ret_backtest))
                print("->", time_backtest.shape, pred_backtest.shape, ret_backtest.shape)
            except Exception as e:
                print("Error occurred during CNN model training:", e)
                # Reshape the data to have smaller dimensions
                X_train_GAF, X_test_GAF = X_train_GAF.reshape(-1, window_size, window_size, 1), X_test_GAF.reshape(-1, window_size, window_size, 1)
                print("Reshape sucessful")

    # Ensure consistency in the lengths of arrays
    min_length = min(len(time_backtest), len(pred_backtest), len(ret_backtest))
    time_backtest = time_backtest[:min_length]
    pred_backtest = pred_backtest[:min_length]
    ret_backtest = ret_backtest[:min_length]

    df_predictions = pd.DataFrame({
        'Date': time_backtest,
        'Pred': pred_backtest,
        'Ret': ret_backtest
    })

    # Specify the unit for the 'Date' column (assuming it's datetime)
    df_predictions["Date"] = pd.to_datetime(df_predictions["Date"])

    return df_predictions

def backtest(df_res):
  # Perform backtest
  df_res.set_index('Date')
  initial_capital = 10000  # Initial capital in USD
  current_capital = initial_capital
  shares = 0
  total_trades = 0
  winning_trades = 0

  for i in range(df_res.shape[0]):
    # Buy signal: If the predicted return increase is above a threshold, buy shares
    if df_res.iloc[i, 1] > df_res.iloc[i, 2]:
        dt = df_res['Date'].iloc[i]
        test_price = data.loc[dt, 'Close']
        #print (test_price, dt)
        shares_to_buy = int(current_capital / test_price)
        shares += shares_to_buy
        current_capital -= shares_to_buy * test_price
        total_trades += 1
        winning_trades += 1

    # Sell signal: If the predicted return decrease is below a threshold, sell shares
    elif df_res.iloc[i, 1] < df_res.iloc[i, 2]:
        dt = df_res['Date'].iloc[i]
        test_price = data.loc[dt, 'Close']
        current_capital += shares * test_price
        shares = 0
        total_trades += 1

  # Calculate the final portfolio value
  final_portfolio_value = current_capital + shares * test_prices[-1]
  percent_gain = ((final_portfolio_value - initial_capital) / initial_capital) * 100

  # Print the results
  results_df = pd.DataFrame([initial_capital, final_portfolio_value, percent_gain, total_trades, winning_trades],
                                index=['Initial Capital', 'Final Portfolio Value', 'Percentage Gain', 'Total Trades', 'Winning Trades'],
                                columns=['Value'])
  results_df.round(2)

  return results_df


def compare_returns(df_res):
  """
  Backtesting based on the prediction results.

  :param df_res: dataframe of results
  :return: dataframe of results
  """

  df_res["Positions"] = np.where(df_res["Pred"] > 0, 1, -1)
  df_res["Positions_shift"] = df_res["Positions"].shift(1)
  df_res["Strat_ret"] = df_res["Positions"].shift(1) * df_res["Ret"]
  df_res["Positions_L"] = df_res["Positions"].shift(1)
  df_res["Positions_L"][df_res["Positions_L"] == -1] = 0
  df_res["Strat_ret_L"] = df_res["Positions_L"] * df_res["Ret"]
  df_res["CumRet"] = df_res["Strat_ret"].expanding().apply(lambda x: np.prod(1 + x) - 1)
  df_res["CumRet_L"] = (
      df_res["Strat_ret_L"].expanding().apply(lambda x: np.prod(1 + x) - 1)
  )
  df_res["bhRet"] = df_res["Ret"].expanding().apply(lambda x: np.prod(1 + x) - 1)

  Final_Return_L = np.prod(1 + df_res["Strat_ret_L"]) - 1
  Final_Return = np.prod(1 + df_res["Strat_ret"]) - 1
  Buy_Return = np.prod(1 + df_res["Ret"]) - 1

  comp_df = pd.DataFrame([Final_Return_L*100, Final_Return*100, Buy_Return*100],
                         index=['Return Long Only', 'Return', 'Buy and Hold'],
                         columns=['Value'])
  return comp_df


def plot_strategy(df_res, name='2a_mlp', title='AAPL Chart'):
  """""
  plot the results
  """

  fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
  ax = plt.gca()
  df_res.plot(x="Date", y="bhRet", label="Buy&Hold", ax=ax)
  df_res.plot(x="Date", y="CumRet_L", label="Strat Only Long", ax=ax)
  df_res.plot(x="Date", y="CumRet", label="Strat Long/Short", ax=ax)
  plt.xlabel("date")
  plt.ylabel("Cumulative Returns")
  plt.grid()
  plt.savefig(f'step_{name}_strategies_cumulative_returns.png')
  plt.title(title  )
  plt.show();

  df_res["trade_bin"] = df_res["Positions"].diff().abs()
  df_res["trade_bin"] = df_res["trade_bin"] / 2
  df_res.describe()

Step 2c¶
Now we compare the performance of the models from Step 2 to the models from Step 1.


Relative to the traditional backtesting, the walk-forward model (WFM) testing results demonstrate significantly better returns due to the real-time trading update and reduced risk of overfitting. The walk forward by its nature adapts to the evolving market conditions and phases, and thus performs better.


Step 2d¶
Finally we compare backtesting results between Step 2a and Step 2b.


This is a comparison of the walk-forward model, as evidenced from the backtests the models with smaller tests (100 test) did better than model with larger test set (500 test), this is expected as the market changes the algorithms prediction over smaller horizon is better
